Interface IVirtualDiskEntry

  • All Superinterfaces:
    java.lang.Iterable<IVirtualDiskEntry>
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    IVirtualDirectory, IVirtualFile
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    VirtualDirectory, VirtualDiskEntry, VirtualFile

    public interface IVirtualDiskEntry
extends java.lang.Iterable<IVirtualDiskEntry>
    Represents an entry inside the virtual disk. This is the basic interface that is extended by directories (IVirtualDirectory) and files ( IVirtualFile.

      • setName

        void setName(java.lang.String name)
             throws java.io.IOException
        Sets the name of the entry. The length of the name is only limited by the size of the disk itself. The given name will be encoded into UTF-8 to save it on the disk.
        Parameters:
        name - the name of the virtual disk entry
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException

      • getPreviousEntry

        IVirtualDiskEntry getPreviousEntry()
        Returns the previous virtual disk entry. Every virtual disk entry (except the root directory) is part of a doubly linked list containing virtual disk entries (IVirtualDiskEntry) that are on the same hierarchical level, therefore they have the same parent (getParent()). This method will return the previous entry in this doubly linked list. It returns null if there is no previous member.
        Returns:
        previous member or null if there is none
        See Also:
        IVirtualDirectory.getFirstMember()

Every virtual disk entry (except the root directory) is part of a doubly linked list containing virtual disk entries (IVirtualDiskEntry) that are on the same hierarchical level, therefore they have the same parent (getParent()). This method will return the next entry in this doubly linked list. It returns null if there is no next member.
        Returns:

      • getPosition

        long getPosition()

      • getTotalSize

        long getTotalSize()
                  throws java.io.IOException
        Returns the total size of the entry. This includes metadata and data. The returned size is the amount of bytes used by the entry on the disk.
        Returns:
        size of the whole entry in bytes
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - if an I/O error occurs
